I submitted a proposal, a Sea Grant research proposal to him, or to the Sea Grant program, and he was looking at my publications.
And this was about the time that I was coming up for tenure, too, although I didn't really think very much about it.
I didn't feel pressure about tenure and that sort of thing.
If I got it, I was going to get it.
If I didn't, I didn't.
But Worth and Allen called me on the phone one day and he said, I was looking at your CV.
Most of your publications are not more than five or ten pages in length.
Is that usual in your area?
And I said, well, they're refereed and, yeah.
He said, I guess they're refereed, but said, five or ten badges just aren't very many.
That doesn't seem to me like that would have very much material in it, very much science in it.
And he really, you know, he's really browbeating me over that.
And I finally, I happen to have a copy of science on my,
on my desk at the time, and I told him that Watson and Crick had a, I saw a publication of Watson and Crick in Science, and I believe it was three pages long.
He said, well, I'm just going to have to think about this project.
He said, you guys have been floating this research in veterinary medicine for a long time, and I'm just going to have to see if I want to support this anymore.
Then he hung up, and I was really worried about that.
I had my salary.
on that, but it was salary, you know, if I didn't get the project, I would still be paid.
But I didn't know that.
I was naive.
I didn't know that my salary was covered, whether I got that money or not.
That was kind of a difficult time.
But throughout all of them, throughout every instance where I had anxieties, Leland and the people supported me.
